Great question 👍 — this is exactly the kind of detail interviewers want you to understand.

You’re asking:

When p = &i; and we do printf("%d", p[0]); it prints 10.
But if I try p[1], p[2] etc., why do I see addresses or garbage values?

Let’s explain clearly.

🧠 1️⃣ What p = &i; really means
int i = 10;
p = &i;

Memory:

Address   Value
1000      10   ← i

So:

p → 1000
🧠 2️⃣ What p[0] means

Array indexing rule:

p[n] == *(p + n)

So:

p[0] == *(p+0) == *p == value at address of i == 10

✔ Correct and valid.

🧠 3️⃣ What p[1] means
p[1] == *(p + 1)

Pointer arithmetic on int *:

p + 1 → address = 1000 + sizeof(int)

Assume sizeof(int)=4

p+1 → 1004

Now program reads memory at address 1004.
